  "prompt": "What are the symptoms of chronic constipation?",
  "response": "Chronic constipation is characterized by persistent difficulty in passing stools, infrequent bowel movements, or a sensation of incomplete evacuation. Symptoms can vary but commonly include:\n\n1. **Infrequent Bowel Movements**: Having fewer than three bowel movements per week over a period of several weeks or longer.\n\n2. **Hard or Lumpy Stools**: Stools that are hard, dry, and difficult to pass.\n\n3. **Straining**: Needing to strain excessively during bowel movements.\n\n4. **Feeling of Incomplete Evacuation**: Sensation that you haven\u2019t fully emptied your bowels.\n\n5. **Abdominal Discomfort**: Bloating, cramping, or pain in the abdominal area.\n\n6. **Painful Bowel Movements**: Discomfort or pain during defecation.\n\n7. **Rectal Blockage**: Feeling of a blockage in the rectum that prevents bowel movements.\n\n8. **Manual Maneuvers**: Needing to use maneuvers like digital evacuation (using fingers to remove stool) to have a bowel movement.\n\n9. **Reduced Urge to Defecate**: Decreased sensation of needing to have a bowel movement.\n\nChronic constipation can also lead to secondary symptoms, such as:\n\n- **Hemorrhoids**: Swollen blood vessels in the rectum or anus due to straining.\n- **Anal Fissures**: Small tears in the lining of the anus, often causing pain and bleeding.\n- **Fecal Impaction**: A mass of hard stool that gets stuck in the rectum and cannot be expelled.\n- **Fatigue or Malaise**: General feeling of discomfort or unease.\n\nIf you experience these symptoms regularly, it\u2019s important to consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and management, as chronic constipation can sometimes be a sign of an underlying condition.",
